            <div type="edition" subtype="primary" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="la" resp="#TS #JP" source="#autopsy">
                 <ab>
                <lb n="1"/><expan><abbr>D</abbr><ex>is</ex></expan> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> <expan><abbr>m</abbr><ex>anibus</ex></expan> <g ref="#ivy-leaf">❦</g>
                <lb n="2"/>Laeto <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> pio <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> filio
                <lb n="3"/><name>Eutyches</name> et <name>Coe
                <lb n="4" break="no"/>tonis</name> parentes
                <lb n="5"/><expan><abbr>vix</abbr><ex>it</ex></expan> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> <expan><abbr>an</abbr><ex>nis</ex></expan> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> <num value="17">XVII</num> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> <expan><abbr>m</abbr><ex>ensibus</ex></expan> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> <num value="7">VII</num> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> <expan><abbr>d</abbr><ex>iebus</ex></expan> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> <num value="20">XX</num>
                 </ab>
           </div>
            <div type="apparatus" resp="#JP">
                <listApp>
                    <app>
                        <note>Text from autopsy. Mommsen appears to have reconstructed the text from the transcription of Ansaldi, rather than from autopsy (note the absence of 'descripsi' in the CIL entry).</note>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="1"><note>Ansaldi: D · M · S ·; Mommsen: D · M · S ; in reality it is much easier to read a large hedera in combination with damage to the stone, than either an extended interpunct and/or an S.</note></app>
                    <app loc="2"><note>Ansaldi: IAEIO · ; Mommsen: [t]·AE[li]O · ; the stone clearly reads: LAETO · </note></app>
                    <app loc="3"><note>Ansaldi: FVIYCHISFICOE · ; Mommsen: [e]V[t]VCHES · [et] · COE ; the stone is clear</note></app>
                    <app loc="4"><note>Ansaldi: IONIS PARINIES ; Mommsen: [[I]ONIS · PAR[E]N[T]ES; the stone is clear</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
                <p>To the shades of the underworld, for Laetus, a dutiful son, Eutyches and Coetonis, his parents (set this up). He lived 17 years, 7 months, 20 days.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" resp="#JP">
                <p>Ansaldi clearly (and understandably) struggled to parse the lettering and the ambiguities between E, F, I, L, and T. Mommsen's attempt to resolve this however goes somewhat beyond Ansaldi's text (which, apart from omitting the letters ET in line 3 is otherwise essentially faithful if confused), and in particular, the gratuitous insertion of interpuncts by Mommsen adds spurious plausibility to a text which in reality cannot be so read. There are insufficient letters in line 2 to justify the attempt to transform LAETO into e.g. T(ito) Aelio (and no grounds for reading LI in ligature/combination), and in reality T is reasonably consistent in this text. It is much simpler therefore to read the single name (cognomen) Laetus, and in turn to assume that 'pio' is an epithet (additionally plausible given the parents' names and the age at death). It is, incidentally, worth noting that the reading presented here finds an exact correspondence in the transcription by Orsi in the museum's inventory (who also read a hedera in line 1, rather than an S). The mother's name Coetonis is otherwise only attested in the area of Rome, but the clear archaeological provenance from Centuripe is against any suggestion that the urn is a modern antiquarian import from Rome. The lettering has much in common with the letter of Iulius Paternus (<ref target="https://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000308">ISic000308</ref>) from Catania of the late 160s CE.</p>
            </div>
